With a week and a day to go, I'm increasing Macron's odds. The gap in the polls are just too big to discount. I'm still giving the edge to Le Pen, not because I think the polls are wrong, but because I don't think Macron's putative supporters are all that committed. Aside from that, from where I sit (an ocean and a continent away), Le Pen seems to come across to voters as a regular gal, and Macron can never escape his identity as a toff - or as cultured and sophisticated, depending on which definition you choose. Either way, Macron seems to me to look out-of-touch with voters below a certain economic, educational, and social threshold. I think it's entirely possible that more people will vote *against* Macron because he's a toff than will vote *for* him because he's urbane and well educated. I consider it a mistake to think that Macron will unquestionably get more Melenchon voters than Le Pen. Most Melenchon supporters may stay home, but I think the majority of those who go to the polls will probably vote for Le Pen. Working class leftists can stomach nationalists much more readily than they can stomach investment bankers.

Let us accept that the polls give a correct estimate of voter's intentions. Then the second round will be determined by the turnout. A high support in the polls (let's say 60%) for Macron, but a low turnout (let's say 60%) could still mean that Le Pen (support = 40%, but turnout = 95%) wins. Complacency and/or lukewarm support for Macron from his former adversaries could reduce his turnout, while the small chance to win against all odds could bolster the Le Pen turnout. However: the calculations show that, given the present polling results (http://www.linternaute.com/actualite/politique/1357555-presidentielle-2017-resultat-dernier-sondage-macron-le-pen-2eme-tour) (Macron = 60,5% and Le Pen =39,5%) that Macron would win once his turnout is 62,5% or above. On average he will win 84,8% of all simulations in which his turnout goes from 55% to 75%, and the Le Pen turnout goes from 75% to 95%. If we only accept a "sure win" when 85% of the simulations go to one candidate, then Macron has a ''sure win" in 70% of the simulations. Probably a bit conservative.

I've been reading today that there is no bloc of voters that Le Pen can tap into to win. This is perhaps true, and I'll be paying attention to the number of undecideds as the figures come out this week and next week. But I still consider it improbable that a majority of working people will vote for Macron. I'm not sure Fillon's endorsement of Macron will matter very much, and Melenchon has declined to endorse either candidate (so far). I think it's a pretty safe bet that something approaching 100% of Hamon supporters will support Macron, and I think the overwhelming majority of Fillon supporters will back Le Pen. However, I think Le Pen will do far better with Melenchon voters than the pundits predict - even if Melenchon finally endorses Macron.

This translates to 53-47 for Macron. A victory, but far from overwhelming.

I dragged my feet about this one. I'm wary of polls because of the "shy trump voter" effect. People with unpopular views don't usually admit them to pollsters. Then again, the National Front isn't new like America's Alt-Right. They've been around and pollsters understand them. Plus, as FiveThirtyEight pointed out, the National Front don't radically outperform their polls. With most of the other candidates encouraging their supporters to vote for Macron, this race is his to lose.

There is something very worrying about the polls for the French presidential elections. Most polls have a sample size of about 1000 to 2000. A 95% confidence interval is then +-2%. However, when you look at the different polls the differences in the results for almost all candidates is less than 1%. This could mean that all pollsters use the same stratification method when they construct their sample. That could make them all biased in the same way.

Unprecedented and confusing since the beginning, the 2017 presidential campaign will remain so until the end. Ten days before the first round of voting, on Sunday 23 April, we have been in an unprecedented situation for half a century: four candidates - François Fillon, Marine Le Pen, Emmanuel Macron and Jean-Luc Mélenchon - To qualify for the second round. The indecision of voters All the investigations have been testifying for weeks. The level of indecision of the French is clearly higher than in the previous presidential elections, except for 2002. Currently, only two-thirds (66%) intend to vote on 23 April. The temptation of abstention particularly affects the youngest voters: 55% of 18-24 year olds intend to vote, 60% of 25-34 year olds. While almost three-quarters of those over 70 years of age say they will vote. This level of indecision has not decreased since Ipsos' previous survey, conducted a week earlier.

I am finding it very amusing that the international media is producing heading almost every day that seem to have very little connection to reality. The headlines talk of a surge by Le Pen, by Macron, by Melenchon or Fillon, or less often a fall in support for Le Pen, Macron, Melenchon or Fillon. Reading the details it then transpires that the "surge" or "fall" is somewhere between 0.5% and 1% in one poll. My guess is that Hamon will not drop much further (there must be some loyal PS supporters) So to get much higher Melenchon would have to pick up votes from Macron, Fillon or Le Pen. It seems unlikely that Fillon's supporters would switch to Melenchon (conservative Catholics supporting the hard-left seems unlikely). It seems slightly more credible that Macron supporters who support him because he is an outsider and are not really into policy details could switch to Melenchon as another outsider. It seems more possible that some Le Pen supporters could switch to Melenchon, the far left and far right seem to often meet at the anti-libera/unrealisticl extreme. Maybe the actual votes will depend on who actually turns out to vote. Will those who dream of a 30 hour week with early retirement, and those who dream of France as it was 70 years ago without immigrants, rush to vote because they think they can make their dreams come true, or do they know that voting for the dream will be like voting for Hollande, who had a dream that he could not deliver.

Weary voters may not feel it, but the official French presidential campaign starts only today, ahead of first-round voting on April 23rd. Posters will go up on formal municipal hoardings in every town. All 11 candidates henceforth gain equal airtime. This will be quite a challenge: they include an anti-capitalist Ford factory worker, a Trotskyist high-school teacher and a centrist ex-shepherd. Among the five front-runners, opinion polls have for weeks made the far-right Marine Le Pen and the centrist Emmanuel Macron favourites for the run-off on May 7th. But pollsters have been wrong a lot recently (Trump, Brexit), the share of undecided voters is high and last-minute surges or tactical voting cannot be ruled out. Already, the far-left Jean-Luc Mélenchon has overtaken the Socialists’ Benoît Hamon. He could yet snatch third place from the conservative François Fillon. A race already marked by surprises may have more in store

The polls are closing up. Le Pen and Macron on 23% each and Fillon and Melenchon on 19% each. Melenchon is attracting more and more of the votes from the Socialist Hamon who in the last three weeks has lost a third of his support. It appears that Melenchon may be also picking up votes from Le Pen and Macron who have both also slipped back a bit in the last week. If Melenchon continues to pick up votes he could challenge Le Pen and Macron in the battle for the two run off places. French voters must be thinking about tactical voting by now. Melenchon's policies must sound very appealing to socialists (reduce the hours and the years that people will work to spread the work between the people, tax the fat cats income at 100%). How many socialists really believe him is a different matter. They must have noticed that the present socialist government did not actually trust these policies and that France still has higher unemployment than less socialist countries in Europe. So maybe those who will actually caste a ballot for him will only be the true believers in socialism, just as the only people who will vote for Le Pen will be the true believers in Nationalism. The problem for many French people would come if the two candidates that get into the 2 round are Melenchon and Le Pen, both extremists who seem to offer different solutions that are equally outside the mainstream. If this looks likely the mainstream voters could abandon Fillon and switch to Macron as he looks less scary than Le Pen or Melenchon.

First Forecast, as always without too much additional background but here are some thoughts 1. 2 round system makes it hard for insurgent candidates to win - in 2002 when Jean Marie LePen won in the first round he was trounced by Chirac in the second round as supporters of other parties rallied around Chirac to defeat Lepen - something similar happened in 2015 where FN candidates were defeated in regional elections after making it to the second round when voters rallied around establishment party candidates 2. The fractured Left makes it much easier for LePen to make it to the second round because the traditional base of the left is split amongst 3 parties. Three weeks ago I would have put Les Republicains as the front runner but Penelopegate has caused me to seriously reevaluate that estimate and Fillon has dropped precipitously in the polls. So the fractured left is an artifact that increases Lepen's chances of making it to the second round 3. Macron (or Fillon) are more centrist candidates (v Melenchon/Hamon/Lepen) and could be stomached by voters of the opposite party in the interest of defeating LePen 4. However, Marine is much more moderate than Jean Marie and has run a campaign that has attracted much broader swathes of support than he ever did 5. Macron and Fillon both represent the "global elite" a much derided class of people whose positions on globalization and liberalism have been defeated at the polls in Brexit and the Trumpocalypse despite both of those events being seen as relative long shots at various points 6. a terrorist attack in Europe between now and the election could drive more people into LePen's camp 7. The Russian propaganda machine is firmly on the side of LePen, partially because she owes them money*

It appears that Le Pen's support has reached a plateau of around 27%. Fillon's support continues to drop as the Fake Jobs for his wife and children scandal shows no sign of going away. Its difficult to see what the Republicans can do about it. The scandal must reflect badly on the morals of a candidate who is supposed to be the moral candidate. Getting another candidate sounds like the best idea in theory, but then that person would have the problem of being the Republican's second choice, and would probably have to chosen by the party rather than via a primary which would also harm a new candidates credibility. The Socialist candidate's support according to the very latest poll seems to be slipping, but that might just reflect a different polling method by the polling organisation. Melonchon's support has dropped over the last couple of weeks. I would expect as the date of the first round voting approaches support for candidates who have less than 10% support in the polls to (e.g. Melonchon and Bayrou) to continue to fade as voters think more about keeping out those who they are most worried about as President (rather than just who they like) So far Macron seems to have the advantage of seeming to be the candidate that is the least bad choice of the most voters. He is not a "regular business as usual politician", he is not of the populist toxic right, he is not extreme left. He can't be blamed for the past mistakes of the Socialists (he was a minister, but more of a technocrat than a policy setter), or the Republicans. I suspect that few French voters have examined his policies in detail, and so he can appeal to those who just see the fresh face. I suspect that few NF supporters really believe Le Pen could deliver on her policies (or would actually want her to). I suspect few Socialist or Melonchon supports really believe that shorter working hours are the answer to France's problems. So if the Republicans can't put up a good clean candidate Macron must stand a good chance of winning as the "change" candidate. Many voters probably just want a change, have little idea about what changes would be good, but a better idea of what changes they don't like the sound of.

Very difficult to predict. Under normal circumstances this would be a two horse race where at least one of the two main parties' candidates would make it to the second round and even in FN made it, most mainstream voters would consider FN unacceptable. But normal times these aren't. Fillon is a candidate that could stop many voters to whom Le Pen could appeal from voting for Le Pen, given his conservative, outlook and as PS are currently v unpopural, this could have been an easy election for him. However, the wife payment affair and the fact that Macron is independent (albeit with PS provenance) complicate things. If Fillon pulls out, Le Pen's position could strengthen and it's not clear what e.g. Juppe's chances would be. If Macron goes through, he should have been expected to capture all the left votes and enough from centre/right to give him the win. But as we've seen elsewhere, the left/right analysis is very inadequate - he is probably considered 'elite' and therefore could lose a lot of leftwing voters to Le Pen.

The undervalued heritage of Marine and Jean-Marie Le Pen ====== 1. The twenty-three deputies at the European Parliament from the National Front, as allowed by European Parliamentary rules, some sixty parliamentary assistants to assist them in their mandate since their election in 2014. These are paid directly by Parliament, within the limit of A total budget of around EUR 24 000 per Member. Fillon's chances decrease while Le Pen's and Macron's increases due to the employment of his wife in what likely was a no-show job (standard practice in France, where MPs put relatives on the government payroll as "assistants"). This is probably a less corrupt system than in the US where the spouses and children become lobbyists or get hired by campaign contributors (this is how lifetime legislators, like the US' outgoing VP and outgoing/former Senate Majority Leader got rich). However, Fillon's campaign message has been that he is not part of the corrupt systeme, so will drain some of his populist support (and his economic programme is not that popular in statist France to begin with). Seems likely that LePen will be at the top of the vote count in the first round and face either a weakened Fillon (unless he repays the money his wife earned) or a milquetoast Macron.

It is not illegal in France for members of Parliament to employ family, and around 10 to 15 percent do so, according to French media. But if Mrs. Fillon did nothing, holding a fake job, in effect, in return for the public funds, her husband could be in trouble.

Revised following round one of Socialist Primary. A left leaning candidate (Hamon) seems to have won this round and the right leaning candidate seems to have got about 30% of the votes, meaning that around 70% of the primary voters chose the more extremist left wingers. Its reasonable to assume that Hamon will pick up these extreme left votes in the second round. Which will mean Hamon is the official Socialist Candidate. The turnout for the primary was low which reflects that the French left has lost its enthusiasm and presumably does not believe its likely that a Socialist will win the Presidency election. However in the polls left wing candidates (socialists in outlook) are supported by about as many voters (about 25%) as the far right FN (26%), the right Republicans (27%) and the centre (21%). The difference is that support on the left is divided between the Socialist Party itself and several individuals and small parties. According to the current polls the FG party of Melenchon (15%) is more popular than the official Socialist Party (about 10%) neither are thought to have any realistic chance of winning, or of even getting into the second round. In the 2012 election Melenchon's support drifted down from 17% to 11% by election day (presumably because his supporters gave him no chance of winning and wanted to vote for the least bad candidate who had a chance of winning.) But in 2012 they had the choice of switching to an official Socialist who had a good chance of winning (and who did win), but in 2017 there is no Socialist who appears to have any chance of winning. So what will left wing voters do? Option A would be for all left wing supporters to support one candidate. It seems too late for that option. Option B would be for left wing supporters to stick to voting for candidates who have no hope of winning, which is likely to guarantee that the next President is either from the Right or the Far Right. Presumably most left wingers would not want that, although some "left behind" voters wanting a revolution might be tempted to switch to Le Pen. In the past second round voting after the left wing candidates had been eliminated has not shown evidence of left wing voters switching to FN. Option C would be for the tactical voting to start in the first round (as appeared to happen in 2012, when Melenchon's support faded). In this case its would seem possible that supporters for left wing candidates start looking for the least bad (as they see it) of the three main candidates. There are more than 25% of voters who favour the left. It seems entirely possible that a quarter or more of them could switch to Macron as being less right wing than Fillon or Le Pen. Although a few revolutionary minded left wing voters could switch to Le Pen I doubt that many left wing supporters would switch to Fillon. So I see the first round going to any two of Le Pen, Fillon or Macron, with the second round going to Fillon or Macron. If the first round goes to Le Pen and Fillon then the second round is likely to go to Fillon. If the first round goes to Le Pen and Macron then the second round would likely go to Macron. If the first round goes to Fillon and Macron then the second round would likely go to Macron. So on that basis its 2 out of 3 chances to Macron. But there is still a greater chance of Fillon getting to the second round that Macron.

P(macron wins) = P(macron makes second round)*P(macron wins second round | Macron makes second round). Now, P(Macron wins second round | Macron makes second round) = P(Macron wins second round | Fillon also makes it) P(Fillon also makes it) +P(Macron wins second round | Le pen also makes it) P(Le pen also makes it) =_(approximately and optimistically) .5*.5 + .95*.5 = .725 Now, assuming that it is an exact horse race in the first round, Macron makes it out 2 out of 3 times , but he is running third at the moment (about 5 points behind the frontrunners), so let's set his odds of making it to the second round at 1 out of 3, so that P(Macron wins) = 0.725*1/3 = roughly 24%.

As the actual candidates are becoming clearer I have revised my forecast slightly. We now know that Hollande is not going to be the Socialist candidate, which raises their chances a little. The polls have consistently shown the Republicans to be the most popular party ahead of the Front National by 4 to 6 percent in the first round and the Republicans opening up this lead to up to 30% in the latest 2 nd round polls. The FN seems to attract no additional votes between the first and second rounds and no poll shows over 45% for the FN and most polls have the FN at around 33% to 40%. The campaigns have not yet started so It could change. There is no sign in the polls of the surprising Brexit vote or the election of Trump affecting the mood in France. This is surprising as the English language media have made a lot of the idea that there is a swing to the populist right throughout Europe. One might have expected that disillusioned Socialists would switch to the FN, in the same way that Trump has picked up votes from left behind Democrats, and that the media claims are UK Labour voters switching to UKIP. The French polls show no such move. In fact Le Pen's best polling figures seem to have been in 2014 and 2015, and are lower now. Maybe the UK Brexit supporters are just indulging in wishful thinking believing that most countries in the EU are going to vote for right wing populist parties. Austria's re-run Presidential election showed a clear swing away from the Populist candidate between the May vote and December vote, opening up a 7% lead for the non-Populist winner. Maybe the European Populist tide has passed its high water mark; voters have made their protest and seen no obvious improvements. I doubt that many EU voters see the Brexit vote in the UK has brought any benefits. The latest polls show that only 39% of employees in the UK expect the UK Government to be able to negotiate a good Brexit deal - not a great endorsement of the idea of leaving the EU. As the FN wants to hold a referendum of France leaving the EU the lack of progress in the UK on Brexit would not be an encouragement (and Frexit would be far more difficult that Brexit, as France would presumably need to figure out how to leave the Euro as well).

The French Presidential election is a two round voting system [1]. Opinion polls showed that the Republicans led by a slight margin the National Front, approximately 27% and 25% respectively. The Socialists were lagging behind at approximately 12% [2]. Opinion polls for the second round Fillon vs Le Pen showed roughly double the likelihood of a Republican victory. This means that National Front will do well enough in the first round to make it to the second round, and then FN will be defeated by a high margin. This is what happened in the 2002 French presidential elections. An analysis by Express reached the same conclusions [3]. This forecast has a higher probability difference between the Republicans and the National Front than the consensus, which reduced the gap in December, perhaps influenced by Trump's win.

This question is really several questions in one: Which candidates will be nominated by their respective parties? Which of those candidates will place 1st and 2nd in the first round? Who will win the second round?

The opinion polls indicate that the Republican Parties candidate should win. To lose the Republicans would need to choose a very poor candidate or really screw up the campaign. As in many elections now (for the US President for example) voters vote against the candidate they hate as much as for the candidate they want. The NF seems to have strong support in 27% to 39% range, for the first round but in a second round the only candidate that would risk losing to Le Pen would be Hollande. Hollande seems so unpopular that unless the Republicans pick a really poor candidate he would not get into the second round. It appears that the NF are extremely likely to get the second round. So the logical thing for each of the other parties to do would be to choose the candidate that can most certainly beat her. The socialists will find it difficult to find such a candidate, the Republicans have several who appear to be likely to beat Le Pen; Juppe seems to be more popular (or less unpopular) than Sarkozy. There is a chance that Macron could win, but the opinion polls that suggested he would do well assumed that he would be a candidate for the Socialists, he has now said he hopes to stand for a centerist party. Political parties in France seem to be much more like the personal team of a politician and rise and fall with their leaders, than the more institutional permanent political parties in most other countries. (The politicians are bigger than the parties in France.) So its not clear if breaking with the unpopular PS of Hollande would befit or harm Macron. Maybe he is too new to have as many voters hate him as hate the other candidates.
